### Main Flows
1. **User Registration & Login (Frontend)**
   - Frontend uses Supabase Auth UI components
   - User registers/logs in with email/password or OAuth
   - Supabase Auth issues JWT token
   - Token stored in browser (localStorage/cookies)
   - Webhook triggered to backend for user creation/update

2. **User Data Synchronization (Backend)**
   - Supabase webhook sends user.created/updated event
   - WebhookModule receives and validates webhook
   - SyncService processes user data
   - If new user, creates User record and default Organization
   - If existing user, updates User record

3. **JWT Validation (Backend)**
   - Request comes with Authorization header (Bearer token)
   - JwtAuthGuard activates JwtStrategy
   - JwtStrategy validates JWT signature using Supabase JWT secret
   - User ID extracted from token
   - User looked up in database
   - Request proceeds with user context

### Error Handling
- Invalid/expired JWT: Return 401 Unauthorized
- Missing organization membership: Return 403 Forbidden
- Webhook processing errors: Log, retry if transient
- Database synchronization failures: Alert admin, retry with exponential backoff

### Security Considerations
- Store Supabase credentials in secure environment variables
- Validate webhook signatures to prevent spoofing
- Set appropriate JWT expiration times
- Use HTTPS for all communication
- Implement CSRF protection for browser sessions

## API Interface
```typescript
// Auth service interface
interface IAuthService {
  validateUser(payload: JwtPayload): Promise<User | null>;
  syncUserFromSupabase(userData: SupabaseUserData): Promise<User>;
  getOrganizationsForUser(userId: string): Promise<Organization[]>;
  getCurrentOrganization(userId: string, orgId?: string): Promise<Organization>;
}
```

